<TEXT>
the bush administration will consider aid to 
the new government taking shape in romania once it dismantles the 
system inherited from ousted president nicolae ceaucescu and 
institutes reforms officials say 
the white house and the state department hailed the demise of 
ceaucescus hardline government friday and expressed hope for a 
peaceful transition to democracy 
state department deputy spokesman richard boucher credited the 
courageous and persistent action by the romanian people who 
prevailed in the face of great odds and despite bloody 
repression 
ceausescus ouster seemed to foreshadow an improvement in 
usromanian relations which have been under severe strain 
particularly since last weekend when antigovernment uprisings 
began 
ceaucescus repressive policies contributed to romanias loss of 
us trade privileges last year the administration was about to 
impose additional sanctions friday but reversed itself after 
ceaucescu was forced out 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said us aid would be 
considered once reforms are made by romanias new authorities 
boucher gave a cautious welcome to the designation of a former 
diplomat corneliu manescu to form an interim government 
he said manescus career has been distinguished and he noted the 
onetime foreign minister has been a leading advocate of political 
reform in romania 
fitzwater said the united states is ready for better relations 
with the new government if it moves along a path of general 
democratic reform the united states pledges its strong support and 
assistance 
we hope that romania will soon join the other countries in 
central and eastern europe which have ushered in a new era of 
cooperation between east and west the spokesman said 
boucher said the state department formed a task force thursday 
night to monitor events in romania and ordered the partial 
evacuation of the us embassy in bucharest when the situation 
appeared to be worsening 
with the dramatic turn of events friday morning the evacuation 
order was rescinded but embassy dependents who wished to depart the 
country were allowed to do so about 20 chose to leave friday 
boucher said 
</TEXT>
