<TEXT>
people took up arms and formed 
vigilante squads to combat looting and thousands jammed churches 
stadiums and schools to flee fighting that has ravaged the capital 
food and medicine were in short supply 
as the us military occupation entered its fourth day today 
weary and frightened residents stayed behind locked doors to avoid 
street battles between fighters loyal to ousted gen manuel antonio 
noriega and american forces 
much of this city of 1 million people was in ruins after air 
strikes by us warplanes and mortar attacks by panamanian fighters 
residents in many neighborhoods organized vigilante groups to 
ward off the looters of homes and businesses who roamed the streets 
at will 
citizens erected tire barricades and armed themselves for 
protection against the anarchy which spread to middleclass 
neighborhoods on friday 
the only way to protect what little we have left is to protect 
it ourselves said jorge perez a 36yearold homeowner in the 
suburb of san francisco 
the citys police part of the panamanian defense forces 
disbanded or collapsed when the invasion began at midnight tuesday 
the threeday looting spree left most businesses and grocery 
stores depleted of basic foods streets were littered with broken 
glass and trash 
many shopkeepers kept looters at bay with guns paying customers 
who lined up outside the few supermarkets that opened their doors 
complained of shortages 
