<TEXT>
a special prosecutor said he was up 
against deeply instilled ideas about what is murder when he failed 
to persuade a jury that the man who caused a bus crash that killed 
27 people deserved life in prison 
larry mahoney a 36yearold chemical plant worker was 
convicted thursday of manslaughter assault wanton endangerment 
and drunken driving his jury recommended a 16year prison sentence 
the verdict came 19 months after mahoney driving drunk and on 
the wrong side of interstate 71 ran his pickup into the front of a 
church bus loaded with youngsters on a church outing 
the impact knocked off the bus front axle the gas tank was 
punctured and a fuel fire exploded into the bus interior killing 
24 children and three adults forty people escaped but 12 children 
suffered disfiguring burns 
kentucky authorities have been empowered to charge drunken 
drivers with murder since the late 1970s but convictions are rare 
requiring a jury to find that a defendant acted wantonly with 
extreme indifference to human life 
in the mahoney case the murder charge didnt stick even though 
the tragedy was compounded by the innocence of the victims and the 
horrible way they died 
prosecutors must overcome a deepseated inbred public 
perception of what is murder said assistant attorney general 
paul richwalsky who prosecuted mahoney 
maybe if this crime was called anything else vehicular 
homicide or somehow the label murder was not attached to it 
the results may have been different he said 
though it would have been of great symbolic significance a 
murder conviction probably would have had little real effect on 
mahoneys sentence richwalsky said 
mahoneys most serious conviction was for firstdegree assault 
punishable by 10 to 20 years in prison the jury recommended a 
dozen 16year sentences and the maximum 10 years on each of 27 
counts of seconddegree manslaughter but it also ordered all the 
sentences to run concurrently 
the assault conviction made mahoney a violent offender under 
kentucky law meaning he must serve half his sentence eight years 
before he can be considered for parole 
